metadata.name: A Burroughs Quote #171
metadata.description:
A Burroughs Quote is part of the fxhash interactive minting experience at Proof of People, London 2022

The birth of the Cut Up Method via the third mind. Dream Machine. Fragments. Morocco. It takes one to know one.

Esoteric rarity. Value is intended to be determined by viewer aesthetic alone.

Chrome or Firefox is recommended for your maximum viewing pleasure.

This artwork was created using p5js.

metadata.name: mezcal #284
metadata.description:
a reflection/meditation on the idea that over time, we hold certain memories as perfect moments in time. they are not still like a photograph. they flow like a river, searching and branching out into the fractal of our existence.
over time they can become something completely different. but if the memory is all that's left. then what was ever true to begin with ?

--------------------------

press 's' to save png to device. artwork resolution regenerates according to window size.

to create a higher resolution image: zoom out as much as possible, then hit refresh.
tested with chrome.

metadata.name: Gradient Ascent #182
metadata.description:
Generates a lo-fi sci-fi landscape and applies effects to the result. Most are 2:3 portrait aspect ratio with a smaller chance for landscape or square.

Several cool bonus features are included. Click to draw the image without post processing which can also be downloaded. The unique effect for each iteration can be applied to any image, just drag and drop! There are also URL commands included for advanced users.

Controls

Click = Toggle Processing
Drag & Drop = Process an Image
1 = Toggle processing
2 = Increase resolution
3 = Save as a png

URL Commands

width and height = Change the output size
hd = Set to 1 to show HD by default

Programmed in Vanilla JavaScript by KilledByAPixel
Code and Outputs are Copyright (C) 2022 Frank Force
Artwork is released under CC BY-NC 4.0

metadata.name: Excavation #53
metadata.description:
"Excavation" reconstructs the digital screen as a thickened, palimpsestuous ground. Elements are uncovered through an archaeological survey of this ground, while others remain buried beneath layers of digital sediment.

Coded in p5.js.
